Beyond a lack of information, small firms had difficulties securing finance because investors knew that huge conglomerates were in competition with them [(
 
  72
 ), p. 80]. In other words, the opportunities of challengers were heavily circumscribed by incumbents. Banks wondered “how a small business could compete with subsidiaries of Mobil, Exxon, Shell, Arco, Motorola, and Texas Instruments” [(
 
  75
 ), p. 13]. Small firms that did acquire finance could mainly cater to small specialty markets. For example, the founder of Solec consciously avoided investing in research, expensive materials, and direct competition with oil companies [(
 
  79
 ), p. 30]. The American PV industry became bifurcated, consisting of one segment that focused only on long-term research and another on manufacturing [(
 
  69
 ), pp. 122–124]. Only independent firms backed by oil money could do both. The divided industry could not put up a united front in their efforts to influence energy policy. Strapped for cash, several small PV firms survived by selling their technology to Japanese competitors [(
 
  74
 ); (
 
  76
 ), p. 12].
